If you haven't already signed up,

256
00:10:41,910 --> 00:10:43,590
then I'll leave a link in the description.

257
00:10:43,590 --> 00:10:46,380
If you've already signed
up within the last 10 days,

258
00:10:46,380 --> 00:10:50,250
you can head over to the promo
code section of Trading 212

259
00:10:50,250 --> 00:10:51,990
and enter the code Tilbury

260
00:10:51,990 --> 00:10:55,230
to get a free fractional share
worth up to a hundred pound.

261
00:10:55,230 --> 00:10:58,320
This is a nice boost to get
you started with investing.

262
00:10:58,320 --> 00:11:02,040
Then go over to pies and
then click the plus icon.

263
00:11:02,040 --> 00:11:04,170
Now you can select
whatever stocks you want

264
00:11:04,170 --> 00:11:05,400
to include in your pie.

265
00:11:05,400 --> 00:11:07,320
For our US stock market fund,

266
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:10,741
let's search for the S&P 500.

267
00:11:10,741 --> 00:11:13,710
This Vanguard one should do nicely.

268
00:11:13,710 --> 00:11:16,470
If you're based in the
US, then you can also pick

269
00:11:16,470 --> 00:11:19,470
the Vanguard Total Stock Market Index Fund

270
00:11:19,470 --> 00:11:21,240
known as the VTSAX.

271
00:11:21,240 --> 00:11:23,460
This fund is like owning a tiny piece

272
00:11:23,460 --> 00:11:26,719
of 500 of the biggest most
famous companies in America

273
00:11:26,719 --> 00:11:29,647
like Apple, Amazon, and Coca-Cola.

274
00:11:29,647 --> 00:11:32,760
By the way, look out for
the terms accumulation

275
00:11:32,760 --> 00:11:34,516
or distribution in the brackets.

276
00:11:34,516 --> 00:11:37,650
Personally, I always go with accumulation

277
00:11:37,650 --> 00:11:39,060
as it reinvests your dividends

278
00:11:39,060 --> 00:11:41,160
back into the stock automatically.

279
00:11:41,160 --> 00:11:43,410
Then let's go and search for our next one,

280
00:11:43,410 --> 00:11:45,210
which is our international fund.

281
00:11:45,210 --> 00:11:48,495
For this, let's select
iShares, MSCI World,

282
00:11:48,495 --> 00:11:53,495
UCITS ETF with the ticker
IWDA and tap Add to pie.

283
00:11:54,390 --> 00:11:58,230
This fund is like having
a collection of companies

284
00:11:58,230 --> 00:11:59,790
from all around the world.

285
00:11:59,790 --> 00:12:01,860
It includes big businesses in places

286
00:12:01,860 --> 00:12:04,200
like Europe, Japan, and Canada.

287
00:12:04,200 --> 00:12:05,615
Now for our bond fund,

288
00:12:05,615 --> 00:12:10,615
let's search for iShares USD
treasury bonds, 7 to 10 years,

289
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:16,040
UCITS ETF with the ticker
IBTM and tap Add to pie.

290
00:12:17,550 --> 00:12:20,430
This fund is like lending
money to the US government.

291
00:12:20,430 --> 00:12:23,040
They promised to pay you
back with a little extra,

292
00:12:23,040 --> 00:12:25,140
which helps you keep your
money safe and steady

293
00:12:25,140 --> 00:12:26,910
even if stocks go up and down.

294
00:12:26,910 --> 00:12:28,590
Right, now those are added,

295
00:12:28,590 --> 00:12:31,535
we can click the arrow
to go to the next step.

296
00:12:31,535 --> 00:12:34,830
On this page, you can adjust
the percentage allocation

297
00:12:34,830 --> 00:12:36,360
of your money to each fund.

298
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:38,310
If you go with an aggressive approach,

299
00:12:38,310 --> 00:12:40,740
this involves investing more in stocks,

300
00:12:40,740 --> 00:12:44,280
which can grow faster, but
can also go up and down a lot.

301
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:46,770
For example, you might
choose an investment mix

302
00:12:46,770 --> 00:12:49,230
where 90% of your money is in stocks

303
00:12:49,230 --> 00:12:51,076
and only 10% is in bonds.

304
00:12:51,076 --> 00:12:54,300
This set up is the
potential for big returns,

305
00:12:54,300 --> 00:12:57,390
but also comes with sharp ups
and downs in the short term.

306
00:12:57,390 --> 00:12:59,370
If you prefer a slightly less risk

307
00:12:59,370 --> 00:13:01,433
but still want a chance for high returns,

308
00:13:01,433 --> 00:13:03,870
then a slightly less aggressive approach

309
00:13:03,870 --> 00:13:05,040
might suit you better

310
00:13:05,040 --> 00:13:08,692
with around 80% in
stocks and 20% in bonds.

311
00:13:08,692 --> 00:13:11,310
Don't get put off by the terms aggressive.

312
00:13:11,310 --> 00:13:12,532
It's all down to your age.

313
00:13:12,532 --> 00:13:14,370
As a general rule of thumb,

314
00:13:14,370 --> 00:13:16,890
the older you are, the
more bonds you should have,

315
00:13:16,890 --> 00:13:20,271
so let's make the S&P 500 60%,

316
00:13:20,271 --> 00:13:25,271
the iShares world fund
30% and the bond fund 10%

317
00:13:25,389 --> 00:13:29,850
and click Next and then Auto invests.

318
00:13:29,850 --> 00:13:32,220
This value projection is really awesome

319
00:13:32,220 --> 00:13:34,500
as it shows you how much
money you could make

320
00:13:34,500 --> 00:13:36,210
based on historical averages.

321
00:13:36,210 --> 00:13:37,710
Of course, when you invest,

322
00:13:37,710 --> 00:13:39,900
you can get back less than you invested

323
00:13:39,900 --> 00:13:41,910
as investments can rise and fall,

324
00:13:41,910 --> 00:13:43,740
but it's still a great way to get an idea

325
00:13:43,740 --> 00:13:47,070
of how much you could make
based on data back projections.

326
00:13:47,070 --> 00:13:50,070
Once your investing is
automated, your job is simple,

327
00:13:50,070 --> 00:13:52,650
stop fiddling and go and make more money,

328
00:13:52,650 --> 00:13:54,510
because the truth is the people

329
00:13:54,510 --> 00:13:56,130
who build wealth aren't the ones

330
00:13:56,130 --> 00:13:58,170
picking the fanciest stocks.

331
00:13:58,170 --> 00:14:01,680
They're the ones consistently
putting in more over time.

332
00:14:01,680 --> 00:14:03,300
That means your focus should now be

333
00:14:03,300 --> 00:14:04,980
on increasing your income

334
00:14:04,980 --> 00:14:06,990
so you can increase your investments.

335
00:14:06,990 --> 00:14:10,080
This is where the skill building
I talked about in step one

336
00:14:10,080 --> 00:14:12,090
really starts to come into play.

337
00:14:12,090 --> 00:14:14,970
If you haven't yet,
learn something valuable.

338
00:14:14,970 --> 00:14:17,970
Do it as a side hustle,
bring in more cash,

339
00:14:17,970 --> 00:14:20,991
then feed it straight back
into your investments.

340
00:14:20,991 --> 00:14:24,180
(smooth jazz music)

341
00:14:24,180 --> 00:14:26,220
The next 15% of your income

342
00:14:26,220 --> 00:14:28,530
should be going towards stability.

343
00:14:28,530 --> 00:14:31,740
This is the 15% that
keeps you in the game.

344
00:14:31,740 --> 00:14:33,030
A lot of people don't realize

345
00:14:33,030 --> 00:14:34,560
that not all your money should be thrown

346
00:14:34,560 --> 00:14:36,690
into growth investments or spent.

347
00:14:36,690 --> 00:14:39,900
Some of it needs to be set
aside to protect your progress.

348
00:14:39,900 --> 00:14:42,120
I wish someone had told me
that when I was younger,

349
00:14:42,120 --> 00:14:44,580
'cause I had to learn it the hard way.

350
00:14:44,580 --> 00:14:46,020
I didn't grow up around money,

351
00:14:46,020 --> 00:14:48,891
so when I turned 18 and
needed a car to get to work,

352
00:14:48,891 --> 00:14:51,350
I didn't have any savings set aside,

353
00:14:51,350 --> 00:14:53,550
so I did what most people do.

354
00:14:53,550 --> 00:14:54,690
I took out a loan

355
00:14:54,690 --> 00:14:59,040
and bought myself a solid
little German whip, a VW Golf.

356
00:14:59,040 --> 00:15:02,520
I even got a new stereo with
the extra cash the bank gave me

357
00:15:02,520 --> 00:15:04,080
and for about three months

358
00:15:04,080 --> 00:15:06,330
I felt like I was on top of the world.

359
00:15:06,330 --> 00:15:08,490
Then outta nowhere, the engine blew up.

360
00:15:08,490 --> 00:15:12,630
I had no backup, no safety
net, and no clue what to do,

361
00:15:12,630 --> 00:15:15,660
and on top of all this, if
I didn't get the car fixed,

362
00:15:15,660 --> 00:15:16,680
I'd lose my job.

363
00:15:16,680 --> 00:15:19,890
So I borrowed even more,
which piled on more debt,

364
00:15:19,890 --> 00:15:22,500
more pressure and more stress.

365
00:15:22,500 --> 00:15:26,550
To me, that car didn't just
break down, it broke my finances

366
00:15:26,550 --> 00:15:28,320
and it set me back a whole year.

367
00:15:28,320 --> 00:15:31,770
If I just had 15% tucked
away for stability,

368
00:15:31,770 --> 00:15:34,050
I'd have been in a completely
different position.

369
00:15:34,050 --> 00:15:36,000
Most people don't have a money problem.

370
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:38,070
They have a stability problem.

371
00:15:38,070 --> 00:15:41,100
One unexpected bill,
and it all falls apart.

372
00:15:41,100 --> 00:15:42,230
Even if you are investing,

373
00:15:42,230 --> 00:15:45,690
you'd be forced to sell your
investments at a bad time,

374
00:15:45,690 --> 00:15:47,700
which may lead to a loss.

375
00:15:47,700 --> 00:15:50,730
That's why you need a margin
for error built into your life.

376
00:15:50,730 --> 00:15:52,350
Let's get into how you do it.

377
00:15:52,350 --> 00:15:56,070
Step one is to calculate
your stability fund.

378
00:15:56,070 --> 00:15:59,940
To do this, you first need to
list out your core expenses.

379
00:15:59,940 --> 00:16:01,633
These are things like your groceries,

380
00:16:01,633 --> 00:16:04,487
rent, utilities, transportation,

381
00:16:04,487 --> 00:16:08,220
and any essential services
like your internet connection,

382
00:16:08,220 --> 00:16:10,920
which you might need for
work, not for Netflix.

383
00:16:10,920 --> 00:16:13,560
All of those things combined
should give you a total.

384
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:16,710
That number is called
your monthly baseline.

385
00:16:16,710 --> 00:16:21,710
Let's say that adds up
to $1,500 per month.

386
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:25,680
Now take that number,
multiply it by five months.

387
00:16:25,680 --> 00:16:28,800
This will equal the ideal stability fund

388
00:16:28,800 --> 00:16:30,630
that you should be aiming to save.

389
00:16:30,630 --> 00:16:35,047
So in this example, that should be $7,500.

390
00:16:37,110 --> 00:16:39,120
So each month when you get your paycheck,

391
00:16:39,120 --> 00:16:41,340
15% of your wages should be going

392
00:16:41,340 --> 00:16:43,320
towards building up this figure.

393
00:16:43,320 --> 00:16:45,510
You might be thinking
this is quite extreme,

394
00:16:45,510 --> 00:16:48,300
and I admit it is on
the more cautious side.

395
00:16:48,300 --> 00:16:51,480
However, I know from
experience that when life hits,

396
00:16:51,480 --> 00:16:54,450
it usually comes all at
once without warning.

397
00:16:54,450 --> 00:16:56,670
So if you only have a
couple of months saved up,

398
00:16:56,670 --> 00:16:58,470
then you won't be as bulletproof.

399
00:16:58,470 --> 00:17:01,170
Step two is to store it correctly.

400
00:17:01,170 --> 00:17:03,510
Now that you've worked
out your stability fund,

401
00:17:03,510 --> 00:17:06,540
don't make the mistake of
parking it in the wrong place

402
00:17:06,540 --> 00:17:09,300
because where you store this
money is just as important

403
00:17:09,300 --> 00:17:11,850
as having it in the first
place, and for that reason,

404
00:17:11,850 --> 00:17:14,280
I've got three rules I always stick to.

405
00:17:14,280 --> 00:17:17,088
Firstly, it must be easy to access.

406
00:17:17,088 --> 00:17:21,060
This money should be
available within 24 hours max,

407
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:22,830
so don't lock it up in some account

408
00:17:22,830 --> 00:17:25,380
that penalizes you for withdrawing early

409
00:17:25,380 --> 00:17:27,600
or won't let you touch it for five years

410
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:29,370
in return for a bit more interest.

411
00:17:29,370 --> 00:17:30,870
I've seen people lose their jobs

412
00:17:30,870 --> 00:17:33,810
and still not be able to
access their stability fund.

413
00:17:33,810 --> 00:17:35,670
That defeats the whole point.

414
00:17:35,670 --> 00:17:37,807
When things go wrong, you need speed,

415
00:17:37,807 --> 00:17:40,200
not some nonsense waiting period.

416
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:43,542
Secondly, it must be zero risk.

417
00:17:43,542 --> 00:17:47,430
This is not money you invest,
gamble or chase returns with.

418
00:17:47,430 --> 00:17:49,990
Whatever you do, and I
mean whatever you do,

419
00:17:49,990 --> 00:17:54,060
do not put your emergency
fund into the stock market,

420
00:17:54,060 --> 00:17:55,560
not even the safe stuff,

421
00:17:55,560 --> 00:17:58,920
because when an emergency
hits, the market might be down.

422
00:17:58,920 --> 00:18:01,560
The same goes for crypto, long-term bonds,

423
00:18:01,560 --> 00:18:04,110
or anything else that's
meant to grow over years.

424
00:18:04,110 --> 00:18:06,780
Thirdly, it must always earn.

425
00:18:06,780 --> 00:18:08,580
Although this isn't your growth pot,

426
00:18:08,580 --> 00:18:09,840
that doesn't mean it should sit

427
00:18:09,840 --> 00:18:11,760
in a dead end account doing nothing.

428
00:18:11,760 --> 00:18:14,490
You want it somewhere that
earns a bit while it waits

429
00:18:14,490 --> 00:18:15,960
without any risk.

430
00:18:15,960 --> 00:18:17,670
This is because if you leave it somewhere

431
00:18:17,670 --> 00:18:21,240
with zero interest, then it
will be eaten away by inflation

432
00:18:21,240 --> 00:18:23,400
as money gets less valuable over time.

433
00:18:23,400 --> 00:18:26,040
That's where high yield
savings accounts come in.

434
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:27,480
As I'm filming this video,

435
00:18:27,480 --> 00:18:31,230
you can get savings accounts
with 4 to 5% interest rates

436
00:18:31,230 --> 00:18:33,990
and with no penalties if
you need to dip into it.

437
00:18:33,990 --> 00:18:35,880
I'll leave some banks in the description.

438
00:18:35,880 --> 00:18:37,740
I'd recommend checking out SoFi,

439
00:18:37,740 --> 00:18:40,069
Ally, and Marcus by Goldman Sachs,

440
00:18:40,069 --> 00:18:41,970
as they're offering decent rates

441
00:18:41,970 --> 00:18:44,940
and they're FDIC insured
so your money's safe.

442
00:18:44,940 --> 00:18:47,730
Step three is to stack it quickly.

443
00:18:47,730 --> 00:18:49,260
Most people think it takes years

444
00:18:49,260 --> 00:18:51,900
to scrape together a
decent stability fund,

445
00:18:51,900 --> 00:18:53,280
but if you play it smart,

446
00:18:53,280 --> 00:18:55,800
it doesn't need to take
anywhere near that long.

447
00:18:55,800 --> 00:18:57,510
When I was building up my savings,

448
00:18:57,510 --> 00:19:00,930
I used three tactics that
stacked on top of each other.

449
00:19:00,930 --> 00:19:03,480
Using them all together
help me really accelerate

450
00:19:03,480 --> 00:19:04,920
how fast I could save.

451
00:19:04,920 --> 00:19:08,220
Tactic one is called the paycheck sweep.

452
00:19:08,220 --> 00:19:12,330
This is when you take 15% of
your income the second it lands

453
00:19:12,330 --> 00:19:14,870
and move it straight
into your emergency fund.

454
00:19:14,870 --> 00:19:17,400
You can automate this with a direct debit

455
00:19:17,400 --> 00:19:20,670
or scheduled transfer so
it's completely hands off

456
00:19:20,670 --> 00:19:24,060
just like we did with the
25% that goes towards growth.

457
00:19:24,060 --> 00:19:27,390
Tactic two is the replacement promise.

458
00:19:27,390 --> 00:19:29,190
This is a promise you make to yourself

459
00:19:29,190 --> 00:19:31,320
that if you dip into your stability fund,

460
00:19:31,320 --> 00:19:33,030
you immediately replace it.

461
00:19:33,030 --> 00:19:34,680
Let's say you knock off your wing mirror

462
00:19:34,680 --> 00:19:37,749
and it costs $250 to fix, that's fine.

463
00:19:37,749 --> 00:19:40,260
That's what the fund is for,

464
00:19:40,260 --> 00:19:41,850
but the next time you get paid,

465
00:19:41,850 --> 00:19:45,720
you top that $250 straight
back up like it was never gone.

466
00:19:45,720 --> 00:19:48,990
Tactic three is the save by spending hack.

467
00:19:48,990 --> 00:19:51,090
This one might sound a little bit crazy,

468
00:19:51,090 --> 00:19:53,766
but you can do it by using roundup apps.

469
00:19:53,766 --> 00:19:56,940
These round every purchase
up to the nearest dollar

470
00:19:56,940 --> 00:19:58,890
and drop the difference into your savings.

471
00:19:58,890 --> 00:20:02,587
So if you spend $3.60, it rounds up to $4

472
00:20:02,587 --> 00:20:05,070
and puts that 40 cents away.

473
00:20:05,070 --> 00:20:07,320
It sounds small but it adds up fast

474
00:20:07,320 --> 00:20:08,670
and you won't even notice it.

475
00:20:08,670 --> 00:20:11,160
The other way to do
this is with cash back.

476
00:20:11,160 --> 00:20:13,410
So if you're using a cash back credit card

477
00:20:13,410 --> 00:20:15,240
and paying it off in full every month,

478
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:16,530
then take those rewards

479
00:20:16,530 --> 00:20:18,900
and put them straight
into your stability fund.

480
00:20:18,900 --> 00:20:21,120
Once your stability fund is fully stocked,

481
00:20:21,120 --> 00:20:22,230
you've got two options.

482
00:20:22,230 --> 00:20:24,360
You can either roll that money into growth

483
00:20:24,360 --> 00:20:27,150
or you can shift it into the final 10%,

484
00:20:27,150 --> 00:20:29,126
which we'll talk about later.

485
00:20:29,126 --> 00:20:32,460
(smooth jazz music)

486
00:20:32,460 --> 00:20:34,830
The next 50% of your
income should be going

487
00:20:34,830 --> 00:20:37,180
towards your essentials.

488
00:20:37,180 --> 00:20:40,830
This is the 50% that
feed you, not your ego.

489
00:20:40,830 --> 00:20:43,373
Surprisingly, over 60% of Americans

490
00:20:43,373 --> 00:20:48,373
earning over $100,000 a year
still live paycheck to paycheck

491
00:20:49,020 --> 00:20:51,600
as most are too caught
up in trying to look rich

492
00:20:51,600 --> 00:20:53,610
instead of actually becoming rich.

493
00:20:53,610 --> 00:20:55,680
This shows that you can
be on a great salary

494
00:20:55,680 --> 00:20:57,810
and still feel broke every month,

495
00:20:57,810 --> 00:20:59,973
because it's not about how much you earn,

496
00:20:59,973 --> 00:21:01,729
it's about how much you waste.

497
00:21:01,729 --> 00:21:03,570
Let me show you what I mean.

498
00:21:03,570 --> 00:21:06,420
This was me age 20, and that's my mate.

499
00:21:06,420 --> 00:21:09,210
On the surface, he looked
like he had everything.

500
00:21:09,210 --> 00:21:11,520
Designer shirt, an expensive watch,

501
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:13,169
and was always outspending.

502
00:21:13,169 --> 00:21:17,400
I was the opposite, baggy top,
cheap watch, just the basics.

503
00:21:17,400 --> 00:21:20,280
Sure, my fashion sense
could have been better.

504
00:21:20,280 --> 00:21:21,480
I could have at least picked up

505
00:21:21,480 --> 00:21:23,220
some inexpensive smart clothes,

506
00:21:23,220 --> 00:21:26,550
but I was young, so cut me a bit of slack,

507
00:21:26,550 --> 00:21:29,010
but here's what people didn't see.

508
00:21:29,010 --> 00:21:33,300
He had $43 and 20 cents in his account

509
00:21:33,300 --> 00:21:35,790
and a few credit card payments overdue,

510
00:21:35,790 --> 00:21:40,790
whereas I had $1,000 plus
quietly sitting in investments

511
00:21:40,954 --> 00:21:43,020
and a decent stability fund.

512
00:21:43,020 --> 00:21:46,200
I'd learned from my experience
with my car loan disaster,

513
00:21:46,200 --> 00:21:49,200
and I'd worked extremely hard
to build my money back up,

514
00:21:49,200 --> 00:21:51,840
which meant cutting out
any unnecessary spending

515
00:21:51,840 --> 00:21:53,160
and looking like this.

516
00:21:53,160 --> 00:21:55,050
Although this might not seem like a lot,

517
00:21:55,050 --> 00:21:57,660
remember, money was worth
a lot more back then.

518
00:21:57,660 --> 00:21:59,790
This $1,000 was a start,

519
00:21:59,790 --> 00:22:01,980
and that's the part most people miss.

520
00:22:01,980 --> 00:22:04,560
Wealth isn't what you see,
it's what you don't see.

521
00:22:04,560 --> 00:22:05,460
I get it though.

522
00:22:05,460 --> 00:22:07,650
It's easy to justify the upgrades

523
00:22:07,650 --> 00:22:10,300
by saying things like, I need a safer car.

524
00:22:10,300 --> 00:22:12,447
This new house is closer to work,

525
00:22:12,447 --> 00:22:14,550
and I deserve a nice meal out,

526
00:22:14,550 --> 00:22:17,400
but that's exactly how
lifestyle creep starts,

527
00:22:17,400 --> 00:22:20,130
so how can you keep this under control?

528
00:22:20,130 --> 00:22:24,270
Well, step one is to get
clear on your essentials.

529
00:22:24,270 --> 00:22:26,160
A lot of people aren't gonna like this one

530
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:28,864
because what many people
consider essentials nowadays

531
00:22:28,864 --> 00:22:31,080
are actually just luxuries.

532
00:22:31,080 --> 00:22:32,430
Essentials are the things

533
00:22:32,430 --> 00:22:34,350
that keep you alive and functioning.

534
00:22:34,350 --> 00:22:37,680
That means your rent
or mortgage, groceries,

535
00:22:37,680 --> 00:22:42,210
utilities, transport,
insurance, and clothes.

536
00:22:42,210 --> 00:22:43,947
Not the latest designer drops.

537
00:22:43,947 --> 00:22:46,530
Just what you absolutely need.

538
00:22:46,530 --> 00:22:49,110
Now, let's talk about what doesn't count.

539
00:22:49,110 --> 00:22:51,330
Takeout isn't essential.

540
00:22:51,330 --> 00:22:54,300
Neither is the Amazon
subscription you forgot about.

541
00:22:54,300 --> 00:22:56,907
The gym you haven't visited since January.

542
00:22:56,907 --> 00:22:58,920
All the stack of streaming services

543
00:22:58,920 --> 00:23:01,530
you keep meaning the cancel,
and the list goes on.

544
00:23:01,530 --> 00:23:04,170
If you are using a gym,
that's a different story,

545
00:23:04,170 --> 00:23:06,806
but so many people sign up
for stuff they never use.

546
00:23:06,806 --> 00:23:09,300
That's why one of the
easiest things you can do

547
00:23:09,300 --> 00:23:12,360
to free up money is to go
through your bank statements

548
00:23:12,360 --> 00:23:14,700
and cancel anything you're not using.

549
00:23:14,700 --> 00:23:15,960
Just think to yourself,

550
00:23:15,960 --> 00:23:19,410
if it's not helping you
live, work or stay healthy,

551
00:23:19,410 --> 00:23:21,630
it probably doesn't belong in your 50%,

552
00:23:21,630 --> 00:23:24,540
so why do I recommend capping it at 50%?

553
00:23:24,540 --> 00:23:26,950
Well, because the average
person is already spending

554
00:23:26,950 --> 00:23:31,950
60 to 70% of their income on
what they think are essentials,

555
00:23:32,257 --> 00:23:34,566
so blocking in your lifestyle at 50%,

556
00:23:34,566 --> 00:23:38,310
it forces you to actually
eliminate what you don't need.

557
00:23:38,310 --> 00:23:40,200
It also changes your mindset

558
00:23:40,200 --> 00:23:42,390
from wanting to spend
more of what you earn

559
00:23:42,390 --> 00:23:45,210
to wanting to earn more
and increase your income,

560
00:23:45,210 --> 00:23:47,130
which is always something
you should be doing.

561
00:23:47,130 --> 00:23:50,580
Step two is to shrink
the two key categories.

562
00:23:50,580 --> 00:23:53,610
So many people talk about
cutting out the little expenses

563
00:23:53,610 --> 00:23:55,260
like Starbucks coffee.

564
00:23:55,260 --> 00:23:58,080
Honestly, I'm guilty
of saying this myself.

565
00:23:58,080 --> 00:24:00,330
However, if you wanna
make the biggest impact,

566
00:24:00,330 --> 00:24:03,300
then you first need to focus
on the two key categories.

567
00:24:03,300 --> 00:24:05,880
Let's start with housing.

568
00:24:05,880 --> 00:24:08,580
For most people, this
is the biggest expense,

569
00:24:08,580 --> 00:24:10,590
but it doesn't have to
grow with your income.

570
00:24:10,590 --> 00:24:15,540
Always renegotiate your
rent when the lease is up.

571
00:24:15,540 --> 00:24:17,610
Most landlords would rather keep a tenant

572
00:24:17,610 --> 00:24:19,230
than go through the hassle of listing,

573
00:24:19,230 --> 00:24:21,780
cleaning and showing the place again.

574
00:24:21,780 --> 00:24:25,530
Even a small reduction or
freeze can save you thousands.

575
00:24:25,530 --> 00:24:30,530
If you wanna go further,
think about house hacking.

576
00:24:30,600 --> 00:24:32,670
That could mean renting out a spare room,

577
00:24:32,670 --> 00:24:34,470
splitting a place with mates,

578
00:24:34,470 --> 00:24:36,180
or even moving back with your parents

579
00:24:36,180 --> 00:24:37,410
while you build your buffer.

580
00:24:37,410 --> 00:24:38,880
If you can manage to limit house

581
00:24:38,880 --> 00:24:40,950
into half of your essentials fund,

582
00:24:40,950 --> 00:24:43,281
then that's a pretty good place to be.

583
00:24:43,281 --> 00:24:46,846
Now, let's talk about transport.

584
00:24:46,846 --> 00:24:50,010
Car payments are one of
the biggest wealth killers.

585
00:24:50,010 --> 00:24:53,310
People lease brand new cars
for the monthly status here

586
00:24:53,310 --> 00:24:56,820
and end up paying for years
on a depreciating liability.

587
00:24:56,820 --> 00:24:58,800
That's why I always recommend

588
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:02,188
buying used, reliable cars

589
00:25:02,188 --> 00:25:05,340
that have seen the majority
of their depreciation

590
00:25:05,340 --> 00:25:08,070
at least until your income
can support a nicer car.

591
00:25:08,070 --> 00:25:11,100
By that I don't mean if you
can just about afford it.

592
00:25:11,100 --> 00:25:13,620
It should be under half
of your essentials fund.

593
00:25:13,620 --> 00:25:15,427
In walkable or city areas,

594
00:25:15,427 --> 00:25:19,650
you could even consider
getting rid of the car entirely

595
00:25:19,650 --> 00:25:22,200
as it can free up hundreds
of dollars per month,

596
00:25:22,200 --> 00:25:24,690
because it's not just the
car payments you save,

597
00:25:24,690 --> 00:25:28,530
but also the insurance,
maintenance, and parking charges,

598
00:25:28,530 --> 00:25:30,930
all added up, this can be a big saving.

599
00:25:30,930 --> 00:25:33,390
Once you've got those
two areas under control,

600
00:25:33,390 --> 00:25:36,660
that brings me onto step three.

601
00:25:36,660 --> 00:25:38,790
Use rules, not willpower.

602
00:25:38,790 --> 00:25:41,730
When you're tired, stressed
or even just bored,

603
00:25:41,730 --> 00:25:43,860
your willpower disappears,

604
00:25:43,860 --> 00:25:47,130
and that's exactly why the
top 1% don't rely on it.

605
00:25:47,130 --> 00:25:48,930
Instead, they build systems

606
00:25:48,930 --> 00:25:51,000
that make the right choices automatically.

607
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:52,500
When I was building my wealth,

608
00:25:52,500 --> 00:25:54,930
I had a simple system
that kept me on track.

609
00:25:54,930 --> 00:25:56,940
Every time I was tempted to buy something

610
00:25:56,940 --> 00:25:59,250
and wasn't sure if it was essential,

611
00:25:59,250 --> 00:26:01,166
I'd run it through a few key questions.

612
00:26:01,166 --> 00:26:04,800
These questions stop me from
buying things I didn't need

613
00:26:04,800 --> 00:26:07,110
and help me stay focused
on the bigger goal.

614
00:26:07,110 --> 00:26:11,790
So firstly, ask yourself,
is this an impulse purchase?

615
00:26:11,790 --> 00:26:14,640
If the answer is no, then buy it.

616
00:26:14,640 --> 00:26:15,630
It's likely something

617
00:26:15,630 --> 00:26:17,430
you've been thinking about for a while,

618
00:26:17,430 --> 00:26:19,590
and if it fits into the
essential categories

619
00:26:19,590 --> 00:26:22,350
we discussed earlier,
then it's a no-brainer.

620
00:26:22,350 --> 00:26:25,140
However, if the answer is yes,

621
00:26:25,140 --> 00:26:27,930
then it is time to use the seven day rule.

622
00:26:27,930 --> 00:26:30,390
The trip behind this is
pausing for seven days

623
00:26:30,390 --> 00:26:31,830
before you buy anything.

624
00:26:31,830 --> 00:26:33,660
Then after those seven days are up,

625
00:26:33,660 --> 00:26:37,043
ask yourself again if you still want it.

626
00:26:37,043 --> 00:26:39,570
Most of the time the answer will be no.

627
00:26:39,570 --> 00:26:42,000
That's the funny thing
about waiting seven days.

628
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,540
You often forget all about it
as the excitement has faded

629
00:26:45,540 --> 00:26:47,910
and it wasn't that
important to begin with.

630
00:26:47,910 --> 00:26:50,420
But if after seven days you still want it,

631
00:26:50,420 --> 00:26:52,950
it is time for the next question.

632
00:26:52,950 --> 00:26:55,800
Are you buying for the brand or the value?

633
00:26:55,800 --> 00:26:59,220
If the answer is the
brand, then don't buy it.

634
00:26:59,220 --> 00:27:01,860
You are likely being drawn
in by great marketing.

635
00:27:01,860 --> 00:27:03,120
If it's an essential,

636
00:27:03,120 --> 00:27:05,190
then there will be an
unbranded alternative

637
00:27:05,190 --> 00:27:08,220
that will do the job just
as well, if not better.

638
00:27:08,220 --> 00:27:10,680
This is where most people mess up.

639
00:27:10,680 --> 00:27:12,900
Wealthy people don't throw money at brands

640
00:27:12,900 --> 00:27:14,580
because they like the marketing.

641
00:27:14,580 --> 00:27:16,410
They really think about the value.

642
00:27:16,410 --> 00:27:18,600
So what does value really mean?

643
00:27:18,600 --> 00:27:20,970
Well, if you buy a $60 pair of boots

644
00:27:20,970 --> 00:27:24,360
and wear them a hundred times,
that's 60 cents per wear.

645
00:27:24,360 --> 00:27:25,193
Good value.

646
00:27:25,193 --> 00:27:28,050
But if you buy a $200
pair of designer trainers

647
00:27:28,050 --> 00:27:31,290
and wear them twice, that's
a hundred dollars per wear,

648
00:27:31,290 --> 00:27:33,780
and going too cheap isn't smart either.

649
00:27:33,780 --> 00:27:35,940
I mean, a $5 shirt that falls apart

650
00:27:35,940 --> 00:27:37,980
in the wash is still a waste of money.

651
00:27:37,980 --> 00:27:40,440
So don't chase brands, chase quality.

652
00:27:40,440 --> 00:27:42,060
So if you answered value,

653
00:27:42,060 --> 00:27:44,307
that brings us onto the final question,

654
00:27:44,307 --> 00:27:46,890
will this improve your life?

655
00:27:46,890 --> 00:27:48,330
If the answer is yes,

656
00:27:48,330 --> 00:27:51,900
a conscious intentional
purchase, go ahead.

657
00:27:51,900 --> 00:27:53,250
But if the answer's no,

658
00:27:53,250 --> 00:27:55,410
it's probably just about
impressing someone,

659
00:27:55,410 --> 00:27:58,320
killing boredom or chasing a dopamine hit.

660
00:27:58,320 --> 00:27:59,610
It's not worth your money.

661
00:27:59,610 --> 00:28:02,070
Once you go through this
process a couple of times,

662
00:28:02,070 --> 00:28:03,030
you'll be able to decide

663
00:28:03,030 --> 00:28:04,680
if something's worth buying or not

664
00:28:04,680 --> 00:28:07,740
without even consciously
thinking about the questions.

665
00:28:07,740 --> 00:28:10,350
They just get your mind
working in the right way.

666
00:28:10,350 --> 00:28:12,720
Remember, it isn't about being tight,

667
00:28:12,720 --> 00:28:14,768
it's about being intentional.

668
00:28:14,768 --> 00:28:18,030
(smooth jazz music)

669
00:28:18,030 --> 00:28:21,750
The last 10% of your income
should go towards rewards.

670
00:28:21,750 --> 00:28:24,090
This is the 10% that keeps you sane.

671
00:28:24,090 --> 00:28:26,640
Let's be honest, money
isn't just about growth,

672
00:28:26,640 --> 00:28:28,290
stability and essentials.

673
00:28:28,290 --> 00:28:29,808
You're allowed to enjoy it too.

674
00:28:29,808 --> 00:28:31,926
Most people skip this entirely

675
00:28:31,926 --> 00:28:34,770
and then wonder why
saving feels so pointless.

676
00:28:34,770 --> 00:28:35,970
As I've gotten older,

677
00:28:35,970 --> 00:28:38,820
I've realized it's the
little things that refuel you

678
00:28:38,820 --> 00:28:39,653
and remind you

679
00:28:39,653 --> 00:28:41,910
why you're doing all this
boring money discipline stuff

680
00:28:41,910 --> 00:28:42,870
in the first place.

681
00:28:42,870 --> 00:28:45,467
This is backed up by the facts.

682
00:28:45,467 --> 00:28:48,810
92% of people say they overspend

683
00:28:48,810 --> 00:28:51,120
after intensive saving sprints

684
00:28:51,120 --> 00:28:53,400
because saving without joy starts

685
00:28:53,400 --> 00:28:55,890
to feel like a punishment very quickly,

686
00:28:55,890 --> 00:29:00,090
and that's exactly why this
10% exists, not as an excuse.

687
00:29:00,090 --> 00:29:03,480
It's a strategy, kind of
like having a cheap meal.

688
00:29:03,480 --> 00:29:04,313
It's a thing

689
00:29:04,313 --> 00:29:06,750
that makes your whole
financial diet comfortable

690
00:29:06,750 --> 00:29:08,910
and most importantly sustainable.

691
00:29:08,910 --> 00:29:10,530
But to maximize its impact,

692
00:29:10,530 --> 00:29:13,230
you have to be strategic
with how you use it.

693
00:29:13,230 --> 00:29:16,530
So step one is to make it guilt free.

694
00:29:16,530 --> 00:29:18,090
To make something guilt free,

695
00:29:18,090 --> 00:29:19,860
you have to see the value in it.

696
00:29:19,860 --> 00:29:23,580
The truth is you can spend
your 10% on whatever you like.

697
00:29:23,580 --> 00:29:26,850
However, some categories are
more valuable than others,

698
00:29:26,850 --> 00:29:28,770
which should make them more guilt free.

699
00:29:28,770 --> 00:29:31,860
The first category is vacations,

700
00:29:31,860 --> 00:29:35,160
such as trips away or
just weekend getaways.

701
00:29:35,160 --> 00:29:36,120
This is valuable

702
00:29:36,120 --> 00:29:38,700
because you are buying
memories that last forever.

703
00:29:38,700 --> 00:29:41,310
It's also a great way to de-stress.

704
00:29:41,310 --> 00:29:44,160
When I was building up my
businesses in my younger years,

705
00:29:44,160 --> 00:29:47,310
I completely ignored the
importance of vacations,

706
00:29:47,310 --> 00:29:49,380
which led me to becoming very sick.

707
00:29:49,380 --> 00:29:52,380
The doctors diagnosed me
with stress-induced shingles.

708
00:29:52,380 --> 00:29:54,284
They recommended I took a vacation,

709
00:29:54,284 --> 00:29:57,210
and that's when I went on
my first ever ski trip.

710
00:29:57,210 --> 00:29:58,560
I had a great time.

711
00:29:58,560 --> 00:30:01,050
Since then, I've made it a priority

712
00:30:01,050 --> 00:30:03,000
to take a vacation every year.

713
00:30:03,000 --> 00:30:05,460
Instead of seeing it as
a waste of time or money,

714
00:30:05,460 --> 00:30:07,920
I now see it as an investment in my health

715
00:30:07,920 --> 00:30:10,740
because it helps me stay
sharp and more importantly,

716
00:30:10,740 --> 00:30:12,600
prevents me from burning out again.

717
00:30:12,600 --> 00:30:14,742
Next is hobbies.

718
00:30:14,742 --> 00:30:18,390
This could be painting,
gaming, photography,

719
00:30:18,390 --> 00:30:20,850
fly a model aircraft, the list goes on.

720
00:30:20,850 --> 00:30:23,187
This is valuable as it
keeps you passionate.

721
00:30:23,187 --> 00:30:25,530
You don't always do
what you love for work,

722
00:30:25,530 --> 00:30:27,110
so by doing it in your spare time,

723
00:30:27,110 --> 00:30:29,190
it helps keep your spirits up

724
00:30:29,190 --> 00:30:31,080
so you can work harder for longer.

725
00:30:31,080 --> 00:30:33,390
Next is nights out.

726
00:30:33,390 --> 00:30:35,607
Dinner, concerts and experiences.

727
00:30:35,607 --> 00:30:38,550
This is another thing I
ignored in my early years,

728
00:30:38,550 --> 00:30:40,110
and it was a big mistake

729
00:30:40,110 --> 00:30:42,300
as I ended up losing most of my friends.

730
00:30:42,300 --> 00:30:45,240
Having a strong social
network is so important,

731
00:30:45,240 --> 00:30:46,800
especially nowadays.

732
00:30:46,800 --> 00:30:49,560
Finally, we have gifts.

733
00:30:49,560 --> 00:30:52,020
Now, I'm not talking about for yourself,

734
00:30:52,020 --> 00:30:53,280
but for your loved ones.

735
00:30:53,280 --> 00:30:55,080
This is another one I overlooked.

736
00:30:55,080 --> 00:30:57,840
You can see how most of the
stuff I teach in these videos

737
00:30:57,840 --> 00:31:00,030
comes from me learning from my mistakes.

738
00:31:00,030 --> 00:31:02,460
Back when I was focused
on chasing my goals,

739
00:31:02,460 --> 00:31:05,010
building businesses and
growing investments,

740
00:31:05,010 --> 00:31:07,686
I often forgot birthdays
and special occasions.

741
00:31:07,686 --> 00:31:10,020
I was so locked in on the future

742
00:31:10,020 --> 00:31:12,120
that I overlooked what
mattered in the present.

743
00:31:12,120 --> 00:31:14,610
The truth is I never really cared much

744
00:31:14,610 --> 00:31:16,080
about receiving gifts.

745
00:31:16,080 --> 00:31:17,430
There's not much I wanted,

746
00:31:17,430 --> 00:31:19,890
but it wasn't until I married my wife

747
00:31:19,890 --> 00:31:22,048
and we started exchanging
anniversary gifts

748
00:31:22,048 --> 00:31:24,060
that I finally understood.

749
00:31:24,060 --> 00:31:25,740
Gifts aren't about the item.

750
00:31:25,740 --> 00:31:27,900
They're about the thought, the connection,

751
00:31:27,900 --> 00:31:29,850
and the relationships they strengthen.

752
00:31:29,850 --> 00:31:32,873
Step two is to preload the fund.

753
00:31:32,873 --> 00:31:35,820
I would recommend opening
a separate bank account

754
00:31:35,820 --> 00:31:37,950
and call it your joy jar.

755
00:31:37,950 --> 00:31:39,900
This doesn't have to be with a new bank.

756
00:31:39,900 --> 00:31:42,210
You can actually have
multiple current accounts

757
00:31:42,210 --> 00:31:43,290
with the same bank

758
00:31:43,290 --> 00:31:45,810
and have them all appear
on your mobile banking app,

759
00:31:45,810 --> 00:31:47,610
which makes things very simple.

760
00:31:47,610 --> 00:31:49,408
Then set up an automatic transfer

761
00:31:49,408 --> 00:31:52,800
of 10% of whatever you
make to be deposited

762
00:31:52,800 --> 00:31:54,810
into this account every single month.

763
00:31:54,810 --> 00:31:58,320
So if you make $2,000, send 200.

764
00:31:58,320 --> 00:32:00,960
If you make 10,000, send 1,000.

765
